Parliament did not support an amendment to release Tymoshenko
The Ukrainian parliament has today rejected a proposal to repeal the amendment of the section of the Criminal Code that condemns opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko.
The amendment would open the door to the ex-prime minister's release, but MPs rejected the proposal to reduce penalties for economic crimes in the second reading.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for allegedly signing a deal with Russia disadvantageous to Ukraine on natural gas purchase.
The sentence is not yet final, the appeals court is obliged to review it in December.
Tymoshenko was convinced that this was a political revenge of the regime, and even in the West doubts have arisen about the impartiality of the court.
The proposal to remove paragraph 365 of the Penal Code, which condemned the former prime minister, was supported by 147 MPs in the vote.
The bill needed 226 votes to pass.
