Brand story:
The innovative IBM begins its second century of existence
If anyone were to look for a term that would define IBM's strategy very precisely, the most approximate one would be "long-term".
For the general public, IBM is the symbol of a technological revolution, a company that is perceived as current and yet has already passed a hundred years since its foundation.
The foundation of this long-term character was laid by the firm's first chief, the visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He already coined the motto that many of the world's problems have a solution if people are willing to think.
His motto "Think!" became his hallmark, around which the future giant's life was built (it was also the title of an internal magazine that IBM began publishing in 1935).
Watson was also the foundation of a carefully constructed company culture.
"For us, IBM implies a long-term thinking, a continuous movement towards the future.
IBM has survived and thrived for a hundred years for that reason, because it stayed true to its core principles, but not afraid of the changes around it.
That has enabled us, in our first century, to transform technology, business and society.
We hope to prosper even more in our second century", said current company director Samuel J. Palmisano during its anniversary.
A Sophisticated System
