IBM history: from the cheese slicer to spaceflight
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York City a hundred years ago, originally called the Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was adopted as early as 1924 - originally it was a trademark used in the branches of Canada and South America.
The foundation that gave rise to the birth of IBM arose from the merger of four companies that date back to the 1880s.
He had such inventions as the famous "check clock", which allowed him to control the entrance and exit of employees.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 also chaired its supervisory board.
Flint hired the head of a competing firm, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
The new leader overshadowed the founder of IBM (Watson's ideas remain the firm foundation on which the corporate culture and identity are sustained).
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, began with the production and sale of all kinds of business appliances, from meat and cheese cutters to cash registers.
During the first four years Watson ran the company, turnover doubled to $9 million and the company's great expansion across the continents began.
Watson was so crucial to the company that, after nearly forty years in the chair, he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Jr.
Under his leadership, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, IBM personnel and computers helped NASA guide space flights (to Mercury, Saturn, and in 1969 the famous flight to the Moon).
Meanwhile, in 1964 IBM developed the first generation of computers, the IBM System/360 series.
The classic "fish", which set the standard for computers at the time, came to market as the IBM 5150 in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, which in turn acquired the consulting part of the company Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began offering complete consultancy and high value-added services.
The strategy that IBM has paid for over the last three years is the Smarter Planet concept, that is, "a smarter planet".
It aims to make a more rational use of technology, although areas have not yet been planned or circumstances have not yet been improved, for example, in transport and city management.
For the retail sector, IBM recently introduced the 'Smart Commerce' platform which enables retailers to manage the entire sales cycle.
IBM has a long history in this country.
Already in 1932 he opened a branch in what was then Czechoslovakia, the first country to have one in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM ČR also operates the strategic outsourcing centre in Brno.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe is in Prague, and there's a world-renowned research team here that's working on voice recognition.
