How have travel prices evolved since 1989?
Until 1989 there were only five authorised state travel agencies in the then Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at the time mostly sold trips only to the socialist bloc, as travel to the West was very restricted.
Czech tourists therefore went on holiday to the beaches of the GDR (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union (Sochi in Crimea on the Black Sea), Bulgaria and Romania (both on the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when you could travel to Yugoslavia, however, after the Yugoslav regime inclined west and travel of Czech tourists were then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely and individually even in socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, otherwise the individual journey was not possible.
Travel agencies offered trips to the West in those days, but you had to stand in line with a sleeping bag and spend the night, or have "good acquaintances" at the agency.
Still not all was won.
The so-called "promise of change" that was the condition for the trips to the West, was not granted to the "politically unreliable people", who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without a guarantee of exchange, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays in their own country, so there were a large number of cottages and summer houses, which Czechs would acquire.
The way Czechs travel has undergone a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 we were no longer going to spend our holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million holiday trips to countries all over the world.
It is a great paradox, which we are not aware of today, that the current favourite destination, Croatia, was not a free destination until 1989 because it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
The introduction of visa-free travel to neighbouring countries in Western Europe in the early 1990s led to a huge surge in short-term visits, particularly to Vienna and Germany.
Czechoslovaks, for a long time, did not get tired of excursions to the West, everyone wanted to see it at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czech groups slept in tents in the park, since our income at that time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or a boarding house.
A typical feature of the Czechs of that time was to take food with them (canned, stewed, etc.) to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech koruna, so that our tourists could finally, after decades, freely buy Western currency.
Our living standards were rising, and with them the average wages, which around 1997 caused an increase in the demand for travel.
With the increase in travel demand, agencies began, from 1997 onwards, to arrange regularly for travel using charter connections, which made travel prices incredibly lower compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts for passenger volume.
By the end of the 1990s, Czechs could travel without a visa to almost all developed countries except the United States, which made our travels even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism happened already in 2000, when it was organized, thanks to a huge demand, the first direct flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country, and it was to Thailand.
Since that year, direct charter flights with Czech tourists to distant and hot countries have been taking off every year.
The exotic countries are now visited by about 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this epoch, symbolizing our post-revolutionary development, came in the year 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States abolished visas for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008 Czechs, for the first time in their history, spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, spent more than 15 thousand CZK per head on trips abroad, including the expenses at the place of stay.
The convened Ordinary General Assembly to elect the President, which could end up again in deadlock.
Czech football has been without a president for almost five months and it is likely that the successor to Ivan Hašek as President of the Czech Football Federation (FAČR) will not be known even after the next Extraordinary General Assembly will take place on Thursday in Nymburk.
In fact, no agreement has yet been reached on the voting rules to be followed.
Without them, you can't even vote to choose between the three candidates.
The candidates for the post of President of Czech football are Jindřich Rajchl, Miroslav Pelta and Tomáš Paclík.
Hašek resigned from his post in June not without first calling his colleagues with the purpose of finding a strong person who knew how to deal with football in the future.
However, after the Hašek era concluded, a controversy broke out between the two federations of the association unable to reach an agreement to choose a common candidate.
This was evident on September 16 when the new president had to be elected.
Delegates of the General Assembly met in vain at the National House (Národní dům), located in the Prague district of Smíchov, because talks had been blocked and not only in terms of the method of election.
No consensus was reached as to who in the General Assembly had the right to vote - only the legal representatives or also the delegates with full powers.
From that moment on, and because of this one point, there was a partial agreement, supported also by the recommendation of the Institute of State and Law, according to which representation by plenipotentiary is not possible.
However, disputes over the electoral code remain open.
The Commission has already made a number of proposals for the introduction of a new system of own resources.
The opinion on the possibility of voting has changed a couple of times already, but the neuralgic point remains the same.
The question is: how can we proceed in the third round to avoid a deadlock?
"The dispute is about whether to proceed according to the statutes or to find another model", says Dušan Svoboda, one of the three vice presidents of the FAČR, which, from the association's leadership, represents professional football.
According to the model proposed in the statutes, the candidate with the highest percentage of support in the federation to which he will present his candidacy will win in the third round.
The Moravian Region is willing to reach a compromise so that the candidate with the highest overall percentage of votes in both federations can win.
The Bohemian side, however, imposes the condition that the winner, according to these percentage calculations, must have a majority of at least two thirds.
"This would, however, take away the meaning of the previous two rounds and would completely negate the concept of a bicameral system", is how Svoboda understands the objections of the Moravian side, according to which it would be better not to touch the order and vote according to the applicable statutes.
Surprisingly, Tomaš Paclík agrees with this, although it is assumed that the electoral regulations established by the statutes of all the candidates suit Pelta better.
"I would like to see the vote as far as possible in accordance with the statutes".
"So that no nonsense is invented about the representatives as in the last General Assembly", says the owner of Victoria Plzen, who is running for the first time as a candidate and who directs his remarks mainly against Pelta.
Pelta is still optimistic.
According to him, the new president will be decided in Nymburk and he believes that the candidates in the future will cooperate constructively.
"All the passions will be appeased with today's match of our national team in the European Championship.
"Football will again be the protagonist, and this will make cooperation more enjoyable", says the representative of Jablonice, who of the three candidates has the most experience in football management, both at a professional and regional level.
Rajchl is the most reticent.
"I hope that an agreement will be reached, but unfortunately the situation is much more complicated".
"It's not about the Bohemian-Moravian conflict, but there are attempts to adjust the rules to their own convenience".
"This may result in a new blockage of the General Assembly".
"In any case, I hope common sense will prevail", Rajchl said.
There's not much time left for all parties to come to an agreement.
Some negotiations had to be held in Montenegro, but who can know until the match starts if the football team will be complete?
The special plane, in which the vice presidents Dalibor Kucera and Rajchl had to travel to Podgorica, has not left this morning due to technical problems in Prague, having to look for an alternative to transport part of the executive committee to the place where the qualifying match will take place.
Perhaps the decisive meeting, finally, could be the one to take place at ministerial level, which, they say, will be held this Wednesday.
Josef Dobeš, Minister of Education, Youth and Sports, would very much like to bring the divided parties into the most powerful sports organization in the country so that an agreement can be reached.
There is a lot at stake: State subsidies, the credibility of football and also the upcoming General Assembly of the Central Committee of the Czechoslovak Sports Federation (ČSTV) which will try to give a new direction to Czech sport after the financial problems of the Sazka lottery.
Paclík will fight for the presidency, because he can't find a more suitable candidate.
If the head of Pilsen's players, Tomaš Paclik, had known before the Extraordinary General Assembly the name of a suitable candidate who would satisfy all his ideas about the new president of the Czech Football Federation (FAČR), he would not have run as a candidate for such a relevant position.
