Architectural historian Meder explored more than 200 pools in this way and presents them in her recent book "Badefreuden": the covered pools in Munich, the historic bath palaces in the Black Forest, the "concrete constructions" in Taunus.
He made his "journey through the most extraordinary baths of Central Europe" through 13 countries: In addition to Germany, Austria and Switzerland, he visited places in Italy, France, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Slovenia, Hungary, Romania, Poland, and a city respectively in Luxembourg, Serbia and Croatia.
This 46-year-old German is a true enthusiast of bath culture.
He doesn't want to have anything to do with sports, says Meder, only the water is different.
He is only annoyed that bathers have to settle for blue tiles and the smell of chlorine, while joggers can breathe in the fascinating smell of the fir forest or hear the happy songs of the birds in the park.
"I once wondered why swimming pools always have to be so ugly", says this Viennese woman.
"I started collecting pretty pools".
The surface of the water duplicates the architecture.
The well-being factor in swimming pools is so great because all the senses are served, according to Meder.
And if the builder makes an effort, the indoor pools can be a real treat to the eye: "Instead of floor, the bathrooms have a water surface".
"On the one hand it is transparent, on the other hand it reflects the beauty of the whole building".
Everything is optically folded: the high vaults, the colored tiles, the trampolines.
The small-format photography book "Badefreuden" provides very interesting information on architecture and art history in the historical oases of welfare in 190 pages, but above all it makes you want to jump into the blue.
Meder, the pool collector, discovers the outstanding specimens in her research in Hungary.
Along with the magnificent medicinal baths such as the 100-year-old Széchenyi Bath in Budapest, there are the nitrate waters in a unique karst cavity (cavity baths in Miskolc-Tapolca), as well as some thermal baths, whose pools are alkaline waters and are located in a bottle-shaped building (Városimál Terfürdö in Jászberény).
Many open-air pools in Switzerland and Austria offer spectacular views: While the whole city looms over the Zurich rooftop pool, one can look out onto the snow-covered Arlberb from the outdoor pool of a bath in St. Anton, and: In the Turkish bath there is a window from which one can observe the practice on the ski slopes.
Perhaps the most extraordinary design awaits guests in Längenfeld: The Ötztal Water Cathedral looks like a UFO that has just landed in the Alps.
From three open springs, steam rises in winter, while the Ötztal mountains rise to the sky in the background.
The Alhambra in the Black Forest
Meder, the pool collector, was not bothered by the smell of chlorine in all the pools.
Many thermal baths smell of sulfur, in the baths of Árpád in Békescsaba, Hungary, the diesel plague is so strong that people think they have reached a bathroom.
The smell comes from the medicinal waters that contain bicarbonate and alkali and whose sap sticks to the skin when entering the pool, a special kind of well-being.
Iris Meder also got disappointed in one place in her search for nice places for bathing, when she wanted to visit open pools and sunbaths in the Czech Luhatschowitz bath, she found a blocked ground.
The 1902 bathroom by architect Duan Jurkovic was closed.
When Meder looked through the collapsed windows of the red, white and yellow modernist building, he saw weeds growing among the tiles.
The decadence was countered by a lovely pool in the Black Forest: the Thermal Palace at Bad Wildbald.
These baths have three phases of construction behind them; not only can you discover neo-Romanesque elements from the time of its construction in 1844, but also an Arabic Alhambra style hall, added in 1900.
