Walls Have Eyes: How Researchers are Studying You on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of the far right in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just another guy airing his anti-immigration views online.
On Monday, Breivik, who admitted to carrying out a massacre in Norway in July that left 77 dead, faced his first public court hearing.
While Breivik may have acted alone, he was far from alone in cyberspace: He had spent most of the time before his attack in front of his computer, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social media.
After the tragedy this summer, researchers wanted to know more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy - you just have to log in to Facebook.
"We realized that it wasn't that hard to reach them", says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recently published report on European digital populism by the British think tank DEMOS.
Facebook's personal information cache is so encyclopedic, says Bartlett, that researchers could simply use the advertising tool to determine their desired demographic characteristics with scientific accuracy - the way marketers have been using it for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million fans of right-wing groups across Europe and then ran ads for them, but instead of linking them to a new band or diet product, the ads invited users to complete a survey that asked about their educational level, attitudes toward violence and optimism about their own future.
By reaching out via Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to study over 10,000 supporters of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - all without leaving the office.
"It's a whole new way of doing research", says Bartlett.
Some of the results are not entirely surprising: Online supporters of right-wing groups tend to be young, male and angry about immigration.
However, in a kind of twist, "those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who stay behind the computer screen".
The work of DEMOS is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new and important tool in the hands of scientists.
Research institutes, medical researchers and political scientists are using the site to study everything from health issues to social trends as expressed in likes, messages on walls and status updates.
With over 800 million active users adding an average of three pieces of content a day, Facebook's "data supernova" is generating a research boom, boosting the number of academic papers with the site's name in the title by almost 800% in the last five years.
To some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it allows you to study people you couldn't reach with a briefcase on the street.
"Before, when you tried to poll people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them".
"You would have to go through the party, and they would never allow you access", Bartlett says.
"Facebook removes all that - you go directly to them".
Others say the site could provide a way to identify and address health-social issues.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison and her colleagues found that college students who talked about their drunken exploits on Facebook were significantly more likely to have problems with drinking than students who remained silent about the issue.
Moreno suggests that fellow students, such as residential counselors, could monitor the site and intervene to help a student who posts too many status updates with his or her drinking.
"You can't treat a problem if you can't diagnose it", said Dimitri Christakis, Moreno's co-author and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Seattle Children's Research Institute, the Washington Post reported.
"We have found a way to identify children at risk who would otherwise go undiagnosed".
Facebook is also constantly "pinning" its own population for data.
The site's Data Team has compiled statistics on the status of the relationship and Valentine's Day, the expected voter turnout in the 2010 midterm elections, and a National Happiness Index (primarily using the information that is accessible - digital freedom advocates have long argued that the site should make its wealth of data available to others for research).
However, Facebook users know that the site is watching them whether they like it or not - the sacrifice of being able to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away is allowing the site to mine your personal information.
But what happens when Facebook users get to participate in a survey that they don't even know about?
While researchers have well-defined guidelines on how to collect their data offline, online is a free-for-all.
"I don't think many users have even thought about the fact that a researcher might be looking at their profiles", says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, about a 2006 study he conducted with students' public Facebook walls.
"As far as they were concerned, it was just between them and their friends".
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there's no guarantee that a research subject is being completely honest.
On Facebook, it's impossible to know what part of a user's profile information and wall posts are true.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do off Facebook are two completely different things", says Selwyn.
That's why, despite his years as a technology researcher, Selwyn believes that a paperweight and a fountain pen are still the best research tools anyone can use.
"There's no substitute for going out into the real world and talking to real people", he says.
"Social research is supposed to be about the social - and a lot of the social still happens offline".
