7 lessons from Steve Jobs' lost interview, playing in a theater this week
After Steve Jobs' death on October 5, there were some who compared him to Henry Ford - singling out the tech genius as the Great Modern Inventor.
But what Apple fans might find most revealing, in a recently rediscovered interview with Jobs that has been dusted off as a preview of a series of special screenings in major markets this week, is how much this creative mind understood about business processes and product workflows.
He was no doubt a self-proclaimed designer, dreamer and hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer and a flow-chart junkie - a man who believed that many executives suffered from "a disease that consists of thinking that a great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] there is an enormous amount of work between a great idea and a great product".
In 1995, Bob Cringely was developing the television series The Triumph of the Nerds about the dawn of the personal computer, and he sat down for over an hour with Jobs for a long, rare conversation.
At the time, it had been barely 10 years since Jobs had been forced out of Apple, and he was already hard at work on his new computer company NeXT, waiting for the popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small portion of Cringely's interview was used in Nerds, he said the originals of the interview disappeared during transport.
It was only after Jobs' death that a complete VHS copy was discovered in the director's garage.
This slightly re-edited archival footage is the basis of Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, a 68-minute film that comes to Landmark theaters this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone who is known to hate in-depth interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly willing to lay out his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And very thoughtful.
At four different points throughout the interview, there are long silences between the questions and the answers -- 10 to 15 seconds of reflection, where Jobs is clearly weighing his thoughts, seeking precision.
There are also moments when Jobs' perfectionism comes to the surface, where he seems impatient because of Cringely's questions, pushing him to move faster toward the issues or arguments of greater importance.
Filmed before the age of Pixar, the iPod or the iPhone, there's something strangely prophetic in The Lost Interview, as Jobs assesses what he sees other companies doing right and wrong, and offers his own vision of the future of computing.
It's one thing to read posthumous evaluations of Jobs' career, but there's something raw and inspiring about the Jobs we see here, the eager dreamer on the brink of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
Not long after I explained everything in detail here, he went and did it.
A quick summary of seven notable sequences from The Lost Interview:
About how he learned to run a business:
"Over the years in the business, I always asked, 'Why do you do things?' and the answers you invariably get are, 'Oh, that's just the way it's done.'
Nobody knows why they do what they do, in business nobody thinks things through very deeply.
That's what I found.
Jobs details his efforts to simplify Apple's accounting.
Unconvinced by the way costs were recorded - often starting with a "standard cost" that was hand-made, and then adjusted with a "variable" - he developed an automated factory that ensured that they could determine business costs in detail.
About the Pope joke:
Jobs narrates the "Blue Box" that he built himself with Steve Wozniak - a device that allowed people to effectively hack the phone company and make free long distance calls.
There's been a lot written about the device, but Jobs' euphoria here in describing the Blue Box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak tested the box by using a public phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another, while creating a loop with as many satellites as possible.
"We were wrapping things around the world a half dozen times and you'd yell through the public phone and come back a minute later to the public phone next door", Jobs says with a chuckle.
"We were young and what we learned was that we could build something ourselves that could control billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world".
We both didn't know much, but we could build a little thing that could control a giant thing -- it was an incredible lesson, and I don't think Apple would have ever existed without it.
Jobs goes on to describe a glorious prank that he and Wozniak almost abandon, calling the Vatican through the Blue Box in the middle of the night and requesting to speak to the Pope, while doing his best imitation of Henry Kissinger.
As several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak with the American diplomat, the two broke into a fit of laughter just before the pope himself was awakened to go answer the phone.
On falling in love with technology (and telemarketing with Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, while hunting for spare parts to build a frequency counter, he looked up Bill Hewlett in the phone book and made a call.
Shortly after their 20-minute phone conversation, Jobs landed a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"That was a remarkable influence on me, it was the only company I had seen at that age and it shaped my view of what a company was and how well they treated their employees".
Jobs later became one of the HP employees who visited the company's research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw "the first desktop computer ever made".
It was the size of a suitcase, had a little cathode-ray tube screen, and I fell in love with it.
I'd get a trip to HP as a teenager and hang out with that machine and write programs for it.
On improvising innovation:
At various points in the interview, Jobs talks about inventing new products on the fly.
Early in his career, as he was selling a handful of motherboards, he was asked by a customer if he could assemble the whole set.
Working on only 30 days credit, I had to figure out the assembly and delivery of the finished devices.
Later, while at Apple, he recalled the struggles he faced in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember having dramatic arguments... they were yelling at me that it would take five years [to make a mouse that would cost $300], and I got fed up and went out and found a designer.
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could build for 15 dollars and that was totally reliable.
On the big companies losing steam:
Long before he led Apple's renaissance, Jobs prophetically foresaw the way many industry leaders would stumble over their vision, and lose control of their market share.
"Say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make better copiers and printers, and what?"
You have a monopoly of market share, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing departments increase success, so it's these kinds of people who end up running companies and the people in charge of the products are thrown out of the decision-making forum.
The product genius that led to that monopoly position is being rotten by people who don't have the notion of good product vs. bad product - the necessary trade knowledge.
That's what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have taken over the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times its size, it could have been the Microsoft of the '90s...
They took the defeat of victory.
On innovation as an artistic expression:
"There's an enormous amount of work between a great idea and a great product... as the great idea evolves, changes and grows".
You learn a lot about the subtleties of it.
There are sacrifices you have to make -- some things you can't make that electrons make, glass makes, robots make, factories make.
You have to keep 5,000 things in your brain -- these concepts -- adjust them all at once...
In the end it all comes down to taste -- it comes down to trying to expose you to the best that a team of humans has done, and then trying to adapt those things to what you're doing.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We've never been ashamed about stealing great ideas.
Part of what made the Macintosh great was that the people who were working on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who happened to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If it weren't for computer science, I could be doing wonderful things in other fields.
Scalia and Thomas have dinner with health care law rivals while the court accepts the case.
On the day the Supreme Court met behind closed doors to consider the politically controversial question of whether they would accept President Obama's health care law challenge, two of its justices, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas, were treated to a dinner sponsored by the law firm that will be presenting the case before the high court.
The occasion was last Thursday, when the nine judges met in a preliminary hearing to thoroughly study the petitions for review.
One of the cases in question was a lawsuit filed by 26 states challenging the comprehensive health care reform passed by Congress last year, a law that has been a rallying cry for conservative activists across the country.
The justices agreed to admit the lawsuit to proceeding and, in fact, a historic 5 and a half hour plea is expected in March, and the result will likely further disrupt the 2012 presidential race, which will be in full swing by the time the court's decision is known.
The lawyer who will appear in court and argue that the law should be thrown out is likely to be Paul Clement, who served as US attorney general during the George W. Bush administration.
Clement's law firm, Bancroft PLLC, was one of nearly two dozen firms that helped sponsor the annual dinner of the Federalist Society, a group that has for many years been dedicated to the defense of conservative legal principles.
Another firm that sponsored the dinner, Jones Day, represents one of the trade associations that challenged the law, the National Federation of Independent Business.
Another sponsor was the pharmaceutical giant Pfizer Inc., which has a huge financial interest in the outcome of the litigation.
The dinner was held at a Washington hotel hours after the court's preliminary hearing on the case.
Among the attendees was, among others, Mitch McConnell, the most prominent Republican in the Senate and an outspoken opponent of the health care bill.
Special guests at the dinner?
It's nothing new: The two judges have been attending Federalist Society events for years.
And it's not something that conflicts with ethical norms.
In fact, judges are exempt from the Code of Conduct that governs the actions of lower federal magistrates.
If they were not, it could be argued that they would fall under the Code Canon 4C, which states: "A judge may attend events to raise funds for law-related and other organizations, although the judge may not be a speaker, a guest of honor, or feature on the program of such an event".
However, the sheer proximity of Scalia and Thomas to two of the law firms in the case, as well as a company with a huge financial interest, was enough to alarm ethics activists in the government.
"This shocking breach of ethics and disregard for the code runs counter to the demands of several magistrates that the court abide by the same rules that apply to all federal judges", said Bob Edgar, the president of Common Cause.
"Judges were booed at a fundraiser gala with lawyers who have cases pending before the court".
Your appearance and attendance at the fundraiser for this event undermines any claim of impartiality, and is unacceptable.
Scalia and Thomas have shown little interest in criticism that they say too easily blends the court's activity with the agenda pushed by groups like the Federalist Society.
And Thomas's wife, Ginni, is a prominent conservative activist.
On the other hand, conservatives argue that it is Magistrate Elena Kagan, not Scalia and Thomas, who has an ethical problem.
Kagan served as the Obama administration's attorney general when the first legal challenges to the law were filed in the lower court.
Her critics have pressed Kagan to withdraw from the case, saying she was too involved in upholding the law to now be impartial.
Kagan has given no indication that he's going to.
