How to Detect a Lie
A glance at the latest headlines shows how serious and pervasive deception and lying are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy trading accusations of sexual harassment with several women; each side accusing the other of lying.
The trustees of Penn State University have been charged with perjury for allegedly concealing reports that a retired football coach was sexually assaulting children.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was "caught" with an open microphone telling US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
Lying has destroyed careers and convulsed countries.
New York congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made a mockery of his denials quickly refuted by irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with campaign finance violations related to the cover-up of an extramarital affair.
And again, no one who lived through it will ever forget the media circus unleashed by President Bill Clinton by lying during his second term about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Legends about cheating on school and college exams are widespread.
There have been cases where teachers have given test answers to students in order to be better seen in their performance evaluations.
Mentors who should be teaching otherwise are sending the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How much deception do we find?
On any given day, studies show that they can lie to you anywhere from 10 to 200 times.
Sure, a lot of those lies are white lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of meeting each other.
Lie detection, or "the locating of lies", is an essential skill that we all need to acquire, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game like, say, Charade, where the goal is to exclaim, "I got you", deception detection is a branch of knowledge based on serious scientific data obtained over the past six decades at prestigious universities that carried out in-depth research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the old myths about lying have been debunked.
Liars do look in the eyes.
They do not always stutter, stammer, blush, or fidget.
Nor can it be concluded that liars are difficult to detect or expose.
A trained lie detector can get to the truth by learning about statement structure, microfacial expressions, question formation, and timing.
I spent several years sifting through the scientific discoveries about deception in the vast and ever-emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that deception detection is a modern technique that is easy to learn and helps you navigate our complex world -- especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, or managing negotiations.
Good liars have the ability to read others well, to make them feel comfortable, to manage their own emotions and to intuitively sense how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men tell more "self-oriented lies", while women tell more "other-oriented" lies -- usually to protect someone's feelings -- that married people lie less often to their partners than unmarried people (but the lies they tend to tell tend to be "huge").
We also know that if you are perceived as a wrongdoer, others will feel less guilty about lying to you.
How do you know if someone's lying?
First, observe the subject's usual behavior.
This is called creating a baseline.
It helps to provide reference points for later measurement of changes.
Notice the subject's posture, laughter and vocal characteristics.
You better know if someone normally taps their foot all the time so you don't make unfair accusations when you see their feet tap in the middle of the meeting.
Next, look for groups of deceptive behaviors, verbal and nonverbal.
Consider these groups of behavior as warning signs, not proof of deception.
People who cheat can freeze their upper body trying to remember their story, they can point their feet toward the door, lean toward an exit, change their posture significantly, or exhibit "post-interview discomfort" -- that exaggerated sigh of relief and posture change once all the tough questions are over.
Often interrogators falsely make it appear that the interview is over just to seek that post-interview relief.
It also pays attention to the subject's vocabulary.
Scott Peterson screwed up and used the time that he spent claiming his murdered wife was alive, launching a nationwide manhunt for her.
Cheaters may also use distant language: "I did not have sex with that woman - Miss Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question in its entirety.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "constraint language" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... as far as I am... to my mind".
This makes the response a perception rather than a fact and is often a warning sign.
There's no magic formula for detecting lies, but developing skills to detect deception is possible.
These skills will improve anyone's chances of avoiding being victimized by the con artists in their professional and personal lives.
