Climate adversity has slowed the economy
During the first year of Mario López Valdez's administration, unemployment and informality have increased in Sinaloa, foreign investment has decreased and the economy has contracted
2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of the Government of Mario López Valdez, self-styled change, which generated great expectations regarding the advances in the economy, but given the climate adversity of the beginning of the year, no growth is observed, instead it is a deterioration in the main indicators of economic development.
The low temperatures in February, besides causing billionaire losses for the agricultural sector, limited the state economy's chances of growth, caused a contraction in overall economic activity of 3.6 percent in the first half of the year, justified mainly by the historic fall of 31.16 percent in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of the other economic sectors.
According to the report of frost damage, issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, there were damages in 582 thousand 835 hectares cultivated, of which 78.03 percent suffered total damage and the remaining 21.07 percent had partial damage, the main crops damaged were vegetables, corn and garbanzo.
The fall in economic activity has generated, until November, a steady increase in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography the rate of state unemployment during the first three quarters of the year was observed an accelerated growth, since while from January to March 55 thousand 053 Sinaloenses were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 percent of the Economically Active Population, for the second quarter the rate became 5.28 percent, and between July and September the average continued to increase to 6.19 percent, a rate that number of people throws more than 74 thousand Sinaloenses unemployed, an increase compared to the first semester of 18 thousand 969 individuals.
Less liquidity
The unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, for economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the growth of unemployment can be explained indirectly, depending on the actions that since public policy have been carried out.
"What we are seeing is an increase in unemployment that has to do with several factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market due to the effects of a restriction of resources by the legislation that was approved in the congress to combat money laundering, and for people who grab dollars illegally it is not easy for them to work, invest and use them in something", he said.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes noted that the increase in unemployment is also due to a demographic factor.
"The number of people leaving the state in search of work abroad in the United States has been restricted, first because of the difficulties to enter, and second because entering they already have many difficulties to find work, these people are staying and are demanding sources of work here in the state, which makes unemployment rise", he said.
Informal work
The analysis of the Sinaloan labor market is aggravated by considering the high level of informality that predominates among working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 percent of the employed population in the state works without being a worker before any social security institution.
In addition to unemployment and informality, another of the labor lags of the state are low wages, the entity has the lowest remunerations in the country, according to the records of the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Secretariat of Labor and Social Prevention.
The average monthly income of Sinaloan workers was, until September, 5 thousand 352 pesos, well below the national average, located at 7 thousand 375 pesos.
Contraction of FDI
Coupled with the fall in economic activity and the increase in unemployment, during 2011 the largest decrease in Foreign Direct Investment of the last 10 years is recorded, according to the Secretariat of Economy from January to June of the state IED amounted to 630 thousand 697 dollars, which represents a fall of 87.74 percent compared to the 5 million 143 thousand 312 dollars registered during the same period of the previous year.
The Secretariat of Economic Development of the state government, for its part, recorded a total investment of 17 billion 280 million pesos in the year, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
The debt
In the face of the economic contraction, the state government requested in July to the state congress the approval of a credit for 3 billion pesos, which would be intended for investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, with the purpose of reactivating the economy, the approval of the local congress was for an amount of 2 thousand 600 million pesos, and until November they have not observed the benefits of indebtedness in any sector of the state economy.
Reactions
For representatives of the business sector, the first year of Mario López Valdés' government shows a lack of government management capacity.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of the Transformation Industry, said that in 2011 there was a lack of harmonization of the wills of the different sectors, including the state government itself.
"The performance of the economy in Sinaloa during this year has been really very poor, we have to work hard to recover the ground we lost in this year, in 2012 we have to redouble efforts, failed to align the effort of all and especially the good and synchronized march of this new team of Government, we hope that the next year is much better", he said.
Economic slowdown
Loredo López said events such as the frosts earlier this year halted the state economy and restricted its performance and growth.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, including frosts, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that does not turn fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows to have an acceptable level of flow in the processes, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year we are closing much below the expectations we had", he said.
Redefining the vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederation of Patrons of the Mexican Republic in Sinaloa, said that it is necessary to move the state towards more dynamic productive activities.
"In general, we have observed that it has been working, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program in which the vocation and the economic course of the state is redefined, because it is important that all the potential of the material and human resource that Sinaloa has is detonated", he said.
Work to be done
The President of Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision for the future that would better guide the efforts of the Government.
"In general I would say that the government has been striving to give good results in different matters, in the matter of economic development there are some advances but it is important that a long-term program is developed", he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown progress in its way of conducting public policy.
"There are elements that allow us to say that the government is being more inclusive, what I can say is that there is work done and I think that the government is aware that there is work to be done", he said.
