Analog blackout in Mexico in 2015 is valid
The replacement of analogue signals by digital is one of the most important changes the world has undergone in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) dismissed the constitutional controversies that the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies brought against the presidential decree that advances the so-called "analogic shutdown" from 2021 to 2015, by not gathering the eight votes necessary to invalidate it.
A minority of four ministers, including the president of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his duties by issuing the decree detailing the actions to be taken to implement the transition to digital terrestrial television.
With that result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic was dismissed for not reaching the qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to pronounce on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and this remains in force.
The draft sentence, drafted by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed declaring the decree unconstitutional, because the regulation of radio and television matters is a faculty reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and reserve of law.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero herself voted in favour of the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies promoted two constitutional controversies to impugn the decree, and by admitting the demands, the minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions in it prepared for the digital transition.
The plenum of ministers resolved to dismiss the demand made by the Chamber of Deputies, without entering into the discussion of the project, also in charge of the minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Minister President said that he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the federal Executive cannot structure through general rules the measures for the public administration to prepare.
"I also do not think that if I did that it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body", he said, adding that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the federal executive, which has a constitutional mandate, the rectorate of the State.
The replacement of analogue signals by digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has undergone in recent years, and it results in better use of the radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
Delaying the change, he said, would be to postpone the benefits of digitisation, which implies a decision of public interest, which does not have only a technical dimension, "since it covers economic, social, political and national security issues".
These issues, he stressed, "demand the operation of the entire established system, in accordance with the principle of economic rectorate of the State, encompasses a group of attributions that the Constitution leads to the faculty of the state Executive".
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world had already completed the digital transition, and had done so through the Executive, despite having highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, by issuing the impugned decree, invades in any way the sphere of competence of the Congress, because it is providing in the administrative sphere the observance of the laws issued by the Legislature, he said.
They are analyzing the possibility of a "vote for vote" count in Michoacán
According to the data released by the PREP, the difference between first and second place in the gubernatorial election is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes for 879 of the 6,074 total.
The possibility of counting "votes by vote" is a reality in the electoral process this year in Michoacán, where according to the data released by the Preliminary Electoral Results Program (PREP), the difference between the first and second place in the gubernatorial election is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total records.
The president of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that just a few days ago, on November 9, the electoral body approved a series of lineaments in order to harmonize local norms with the federal reform in electoral matters.
As will be recalled, Michoacán did not homologate its Political Constitution or its State Electoral Code or its Electoral Justice Law, since the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the legal deadline so that they could enter into force in the current electoral process and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel omitted its publication in the deadlines provided for in the Law of the State Official Journal, with the argument that he had some objections.
On November 9, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional controversy promoted by the local Legislative Power and described the state's vote for constitutional reforms as "invalid and illegal", since it has no right to "sanction or veto them".
Interviewed about the possibility of "voting by vote", María de los Ángeles Llanderal said that thanks to the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the General Council of the IEM, it will be possible for the local electoral body to carry out partial and total recounting of the voting.
The partial counting of votes may therefore be carried out for one or more electoral packages if: the results of the voting are not the same; the vote counting report is not in the register of the polling station or is not in the possession of the polling station president; or there are obvious errors or alterations in the voting records.
Furthermore, the total number of votes received in all polling booths may be counted when there is evidence that the difference between the candidate who is presumed to have won the election in question and the candidate who has obtained the second place in the vote is equal to or less than one percentage point; provided that there is an express request at the beginning of the sitting from the representative of the party and/or coalition which nominated the second of the candidates indicated.
The total count of the votes may also be carried out if it is established at the end of the ordinary count that the difference between the presumed winner and the second-placed candidate is equal to or less than one percentage point, provided that there is an express request from the representative of the political party whose candidate came in second place, in which case the electoral packages which have been the subject of partial counting shall be excluded.
It should be mentioned that the election of Morelia is in this situation, where according to the PREP the difference between the first and second place is only 0.16 percent, although without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total acts.
