The new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday
The prime minister-designate, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the president of Italy to introduce the new government that will face a crisis that has placed that country on the brink of economic disaster.
The newly appointed Italian Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet with the Italian President on Wednesday to introduce the new government that will face a crisis that has brought Italy to the brink of economic disaster and endangered the entire eurozone.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, will meet with the president, Giorgio Napolitano, on Wednesday to confirm that he can form a government.
He is expected to present a cabinet made up mostly of technocrats, though it is unclear when the new executive will take office.
Monti said he would present the president with the results of his talks with the political parties in their attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in the ability of our country to overcome this difficult phase", the former European commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly say he will be able to form a government but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles have been overcome.
The "framework is now well defined", he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, much less than normal, as Italy battles a political and financial crisis that has driven its debt costs to unsustainable levels.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must approve a tough austerity package demanded by European leaders to regain battered confidence in Italy.
Underlining the pressure on Monti to act quickly, the instability in the markets put the yield on Italy's BTP 10-year bonds above 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland were forced to be bailed out.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of Italian employers' union Confindustria, told the press after meeting with Monti: "We said we would support this government very much".
We believe that this government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this emergency situation.
Monti's chances of success were boosted considerably by the backing of Silvio Berlusconi's PDL party, which the crisis forced to resign on Saturday.
"We believe that the efforts of Professor Monti are destined to have a good result", Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centre-right party, told the press.
The support of the PDL, Italy's largest party, is significant because until now many of its members had opposed the technocratic majority government that Monti is forming.
Parliamentary support
The new Monti government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what will likely be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockage or delay in their efforts could trigger a devastating new attack by the financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks added to the pressure by warning that a failure of Monti would be a disaster.
Monti began her consultations with political parties, trade unions and business groups, as well as youth and women's organizations, on Monday.
He'll end his round of meetings on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who has enabled an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite late last week when it became clear that Berlusconi would resign, Italian debt costs have now returned to critical levels amid uncertainty over whether the new prime minister will be successful.
Bailing out Italy, with a public debt of 1.8 trillion euros, would be too much for the current financial defenses of the eurozone.
Monti has said his government should last until the next election, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement reforms before moving the election forward.
Monti has said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the big parties insist that it should be made up of only technicians, an indication of his reservations about a process forced by financial pressure.
Political sources pointed out that mutual mistrust and disagreements between the parties are complicating the attempt to include political figures.
