"Going to Costa Rica is a dream come true"
In an exclusive interview with Viva, bassist Jeff Ament of Pearl Jam said the band is ready to deliver one of their best concerts ever next Sunday at the National Stadium.
It's been more than 20 years of waiting, but the band says that for them too it will be to make the dream of playing in the country a reality.
Bass player and founding member Jeff Ament said, speaking exclusively with Viva from Brazil last week.
The group is on the South American leg of their tour celebrating two decades of work and on Sunday 20 will make their only stop in Central America.
That day they will perform at the National Stadium, starting at 7:30 p.m., along with the Angolan band The X and the nationals of Las Robertas.
This is an excerpt from the conversation, the full transcript of which is at The Nation on the Internet.
For their Costa Rican fans, it's a dream come true for Pearl Jam to play in Costa Rica, are they aware of what their fans are going through?
Going to Costa Rica is a dream come true for us, too.
This is only our second time in South and Central America and so far it's been great.
I've been to Costa Rica only once and on vacation; it's such a beautiful country and I think we're going to be able to stay there for a few days.
So we're excited to get our music out there.
I ask because there's a kind of devotion to the band, the fans live with intensity the days before.
What do you say to your most ardent followers?
Thank you for sticking by us through all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica; thank you for waiting so long and we're sorry that it took us so long to get there.
Some people are even already referring to their concert as the biggest show of the year.
Does that add a little pressure to your visit?
Some of the biggest shows we've played in the last 21 years have happened in the last couple of weeks.
We played a couple of huge shows in Sao Paulo and we hope that that's got us in shape for this gig in Costa Rica.
We're really looking forward to playing there.
We love that country, we love surfing and the jungle, and for both, Costa Rica is among the best in the world.
How did you guys discover Costa Rica and its surfing waves?
We have a lot of friends who are surfers and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves there are amazing.
My friends always went surfing to Costa Rica and Nicaragua, along with Mexico, are great places to surf, and that's how we found out, through people who love to surf.
Seeing the tour, they've been coming in delivering huge shows with a lot of songs.
What are you planning for your Costa Rican show?
Since we've never played there before, we have no restrictions on what we can do.
We're gonna try to put on the best show possible with a good variety of songs; we're gonna try to play a couple of songs from each album and give our fans a good, diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
What's this about?
I think it's partly because we have nine albums and we can play over 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, so it's hard to pick which songs to play every night.
When we have two or three songs in our repertoire that we haven't played for a while, it keeps us focused and it also keeps us amazed because it reminds us of the reasons why we liked those songs and that we might have forgotten.
That makes the show more interesting for us and therefore, I think it also makes it more interesting for people.
With this tour, they're celebrating 20 years of touring.
Looking back, is it hard to believe all that they have accomplished?
Yes, it is.
First of all, I don't think any of us imagined that we'd be in a big rock band and having done it for over 20 years makes it seem like a dream.
We keep counting our blessings and we're so excited that we can keep making music together.
We all love each other and we all love making music.
We're lucky to go to places in the world we've always wanted to go.
Things couldn't be better for us.
What did it mean to you to be a fundamental part of the rise of grunge?
It's always been an honor to be a part of that group of great bands.
We're very close friends with the people from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It's amazing when a movement comes from a group of friends, and it's rare.
Every now and then, a band from one city comes out, but it's much stranger when five or ten bands come out of the same city at the same time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year, we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on tour, so we're lucky to be friends with all of them still and we're honored to be a part of that Seattle sound that came out of it.
It's also very strange that a band like yourselves can stay together with the same members for so long.
Yeah, the four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which, by itself, is a lot longer than most bands last.
First, I think we're all lucky to be alive, and second, we all care about each other.
We are all very close friends and thanks to that, musical avenues have also been opened which give each one the freedom to experiment.
We trust each other with each other's music and it couldn't be better.
Your relationship with the word fame has not been easy, but thanks to your success, you have been able to do whatever you want.
How do they find balance?
As we've grown, it's been easier to find a balance.
We make sure you don't get too much on the road because it's easy to fall into that game of the big crowds and the people who love your music.
As long as you remember that people are there for the music, that's a reminder that you should respect the music and what it brought, not get all worked up about being famous and being a rock star, which is something that none of us really care about.
How do you remember your other project Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote some really good songs and it was kind of great at first.
We were a band for almost three years and we never released an album until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
There was a lot of frustration because it was going to be so long and most importantly we're still very good friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who started in the band with us and when I hear a song or I see a picture I think about the amazing person that Andy was and how he made me laugh, it was always a pleasure to go to work, laugh, talk about music and football and so much more.
He was an amazing human being and we missed him.
The national band Las Robertas will be the one in charge of opening the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know her work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose her for the opening?
Yeah, the production sent us videos with various proposals and that was the band we liked the most, so we're looking forward to seeing what Las Robertas can offer live and it should be very entertaining.
Why do they always change the lyrics to Yellow Ledbetter live?
That's a question for Ed, so I don't know.
He sings it and I think he does it with the first thing that comes to mind.
As a bass player, what are your influences?
There are so many.
Some of the first people I can think of are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C.J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
So many I could talk all afternoon about the bass players I love.
How has Pearl Jam managed to keep grunge relevant despite it no longer being a fad?
I think all of us have always felt a little bit disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think about it, it reminds me of the bands that I mentioned earlier, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana, and all the ones that came out around the same time, and if there's relevance now, I think it's a wonderful thing because it's music that's worth listening to, and bands like Mudhoney are making better music now than ever.
At first, his music had a darker content and now it has become more positive.
Why this change?
It's interesting because I think there's a couple of songs on the new album that maybe seem lighter, but there are also songs, like The End or Just Breathe that qualify as very dark songs even though they can sound a little bit positive.
With both of them, when Ed played them for me, I cried when I heard them and they're deeply dark songs.
I think when you grow up and there's some trauma in your life and you lose a family member or a friend, those things start to influence your art and your music and those two songs, without a doubt, represent that to me.
I also think that you can be a happy person and still be able to make music that's dark.
Peru:
Fujimori is admitted again for medical examinations
Former president Alberto Fujimori was admitted to a public hospital on Tuesday to be evaluated for the loss of muscle strength he has in his legs, his head doctor reported.
Fujimori, 72, who is serving a 25-year prison sentence for human rights violations committed during his 1990-2000 rule, suffers from several ailments, including a tongue cancer for which he has been operated on four times and is being kept under control.
Congressman Alejandro Aguinaga, who is his personal physician, told the N TV channel that Fujimori will be evaluated for three days at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases to determine the reason for the pain and loss of strength in his lower limbs.
Aguinaga commented that in his opinion Fujimori would be a candidate to obtain the benefit of the pardon for humanitarian reasons, however, he said that he does not want it because he knows he is innocent.
He was operated four times for cancer of the tongue, has a weight loss of 18 kilos to which other pathologies have been added such as severe erosive gastritis, pancreatic cyst, kidney stones, arterial hypertension and circulatory problems in the legs, the doctor listed.
Fujimori has been in prison since September 2007 in the National Police Special Operations Directorate.
In April 2009 he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the killing of 25 people by an army annihilation squad that operated clandestinely in the early years of his government.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political ties
An official delegation, headed by Uruguayan President José Mujica and made up of several ministers and businessmen, will begin a visit to Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two nations and discuss political issues in the region.
Mujica will meet next Wednesday with his Mexican counterpart, Felipe Calderón, the highest point of an extensive agenda of meetings with political, commercial authorities and a meeting with the community of Uruguayans living in Mexico, according to the agenda released by the Uruguayan Presidency.
The meeting between the two presidents, in the city of Guadalajara, will be "propitious for the exchange of information on all political matters between the two nations", according to the presidency of the South American country on its website.
According to local media, Mujica would seek to get Calderón to support Uruguay in the incident with France that arose when the French president, Nicolas Sarkozy, included the South American country in a list of tax havens, at the G20 meeting in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries which remained tax havens, a statement which provoked the rejection of Uruguay and the call for consultation of its ambassador in the European country.
Mexico has been the chair of the G20 group of the world's most powerful emerging and developed countries since November, and has an agreement with the South American country to exchange tax information to avoid double taxation since January of this year.
The Uruguayan government has in recent years tried to speed up the implementation of tax-exchange agreements in order to get out of the "grey list" of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), consisting of countries that did not implement all international standards of cooperation in tax matters.
In the commercial field, Mexico and Uruguay have had a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) in force since 2004, which has increased the exchange of goods between both nations.
The mustache plumber is going all three dimensions with "Super Mario 3D Land"
Super Mario has fought tirelessly for 25 years to save Princess Peach from the evil Bowser, but never before in three dimensions: in "Super Mario 3D Land" he will fight for the girl's love in stereoscopic technology.
The title, which is coming to stores worldwide this month, was designed from the start to take advantage of the features of the Nintendo 3DS handheld console, which allows play in three dimensions without the need to use glasses.
"Mario is the character who has to say how the stereoscopy without glasses should work", said the responsible for specialized press of Nintendo in Spain, Omar Álvarez, during the presentation of the video game in Madrid.
Álvarez stated that "Super Mario 3D Land" is "Nintendo's first video game originally designed for that support", as previously hits like "Star Fox 64 3D" or "Zelda: Ocarine of time 3D" were adaptations of existing titles.
The Nintendo spokesman has maintained that, despite being in 3D, "Super Mario 3D Land" is an "accessible" video game that allows you to enjoy a fast and fluid gameplay.
Álvarez has stated that "Super Mario 3D Land" contains two games in one: the first part is "simple" to hook the less skilled users.
Once overcome, the more expert players can take a "second turn" at the levels of play, which this time present greater difficulty.
In addition, users will be able to choose in real time between an "aggressive D" or one that only affects the depth of the action, but it will be necessary to play in three dimensions in order to overcome the different challenges and "not succumb to optical illusions".
This foray of Super Mario into the three dimensions also means the return of the character to a portable console, a fact that had not occurred since 2005.
In this video game Nintendo nods to the fans of the saga and repeats the formula of the success of the previous installments, consisting of the plumber with a mustache will have to travel through mined platforms of dangers with the aim of freeing Princess Peach.
Although the player will find novelties in the moves, the environments, the costumes and the enemies and also a "playable" Luigi.
Colom backs Portillo's extradition to the US
President Álvaro Colom announced Tuesday that he has given the go-ahead for the extradition of former governor Alfonso Portillo to answer in the United States for the conspiracy to launder US$70 million.
Thus ends the process for Guatemala to respond to the request of the northern country that claimed Portillo to try him there.
In a press conference, Colom said that his decision was based on the independence of the judiciary and the executive, taking into account that a sentencing court had already ordered the extradition.
He said that during his term of office he "did not put his hands" in judicial resolutions and gave the go-ahead to all the extraditions he has known.
In addition to Portillo, Sergio Ruano Marroquín will be extradited, for murder and serious injuries, and Edgar Estrada Morales and Víctor Estrada Paredes, both for drug trafficking.
What Colom did is an executive procedure after all the judicial and constitutional instances to prosecute the former president between 2000 and 2004 were exhausted.
According to decisions of the Fifth Criminal Court and the Constitutional Court (CC), Portillo should be extradited once he has solved his legal situation in Guatemala and his human rights are guaranteed.
Portillo was acquitted of embezzling Q120 million from the Ministry of Defense when he was president, which was the process that preceded extradition, but the Public Ministry appealed and reactivated the case.
Trinijove has helped 6,000 at-risk youth
The entity was born to prevent the fall in the marginality of children without training
The balance of the first 25 years of the Trinijove social support institution is important: 6,000 young people at risk of exclusion have received help to overcome a difficult situation throughout this quarter of a century.
In addition, there are currently over 100 jobs for this social group.
The anniversary was celebrated yesterday in the old factory complex of Fabra i Coats, with over 300 people in attendance.
Trinijove was founded in the Trinitat Vella district in 1986 with the aim of helping young people with little education, without work, with problems of upbringing or in a situation of marginalization.
Yesterday's celebration in Sant Andreu brought together a large number of leaders from organizations and institutions that have collaborated with the association for 25 years.
The varied political representation, in the midst of the elections, showed the unity of the work carried out by Trinijove.
The event was attended by the President of the Generalitat, Artur Mas, and his predecessor Jordi Pujol, the Ex-Conseller of Socialist Education, Ernest Maragall, and the former mayor and current ecosocialist councilor Ricard Gomà.
The current Conseller for Social Welfare and Family, Josep Lluís Cleries, and the Director General of the Social Work of La Caixa, Jaume Lanaspa, also attended the Fabra i Coats' main hall.
Mas said that Trinijove was born in a very difficult time and that the current one is also, but added that the work done so far "is a good basis".
The President pointed to Trinijove as an example of how to fight against bad circumstances and to give hope to people in difficulty.
"The crisis is not something new for the entity and for the work it does", he said.
They evicted an occupied farm where they used to hold macro-fests
The invaders had taken over 11 of the 13 floors of the building, at Balmes, 51
All 12 occupants left the estate yesterday at noon without offering any resistance.
It seems that the nightmare of the residents of 51 Balmes Street has come to an end.
Twelve people left yesterday at noon voluntarily the building they occupied illegally, and where they organized macrofiestas that despaired the neighborhood, by judicial order and without the need for police intervention.
When the operation was completed, the door lock was changed to prevent a repeat of the situation.
"From now on there will be an access control", the administrator said.
The squatters, who had invaded 11 of the 13 floors of the building - the rest are inhabited - took away all the electrical installation and part of the water installation, in addition to painting the walls and leaving all kinds of waste, especially cans of alcoholic beverages.
The first three floors were the scene of the mass parties, which lasted up to two days and made the tenants desperate.
Next to the building is a nightclub, Balmes 51, which has also been damaged.
The owner, Maria Pantinat, told Europa Press that since the building was occupied, business has fallen by 80%.
The owner of the disco points out that the invaders of the estate were unfair competition, since they sold the drinks for three euros, while in the disco they are worth 10.
In addition, the owner of the entertainment venue had had to respond to neighbouring complaints about noise, while, according to her, the disturbances were not caused by the customers of the disco, but by the inhabitants of the occupied house and, above all, the attendees of the parties organized there, which had increased their frequency and intensity in recent weeks, according to the angry neighbors of the area.
The manager of the disco explained that the inconvenience was so great that she even reached an agreement with the owner of the building and nine months ago that "forgives" the rent.
The City Guard also confirmed that during the last weeks had received more complaints from neighbors about the situation.
The president of the municipal group of the PP in the town hall, Alberto Fernández Díaz, had claimed last week "to immediately evict the building to end the problems of coexistence and civicism that produce the neighbors, as well as the degradation of the area".
The popular leader explained that before the summer there was only one floor of the building occupied, but over the past months the squatters had been entering all the floors of the building and almost all the floors, and that in some even there have been robberies.
He added that "it is necessary to put an end to impunity and to be firm against the inquisitiveness that has been generated in the estate".
Also yesterday, the Mossos evicted a building in Nou Barris.
At 3:30 p.m. the police went to 35 rue de Mont-ral, after receiving a call from a neighbor who had observed that four people were entering the building.
All four were arrested on the spot.
Park or mountain?
Architects agree on the timing of the call beyond controversy over fees
The municipal competition on the 16 doors reopens the debate on the role of Collserola in Barcelona
In the mid-1980s, at the height of the now defunct Corporación Metropolitana de Barcelona (CMB), this Administration printed some promotional cards for Collserola.
The brochure defined the mountain as the great park of metropolitan Barcelona.
In fact, it was accompanied by a comparison, in figures, with New York's Central Park.
With the death of the CMB, in 1987, the park was again situated, in the imagination of many, as the upper limit of Barcelona, being the Catalan capital of the few that are not oriented on the north-south axis but up (mountain) -down (sea).
The classification of Collserola as a natural park is based on this idea.
The reference was no longer Central Park but Yellowstone, with the wild boar as the Yogi bear.
These were in place until, in September, the city council called a mega competition consisting of 16 contests for as many other access gates to Collserola.
A gate is a park, for sure.
Either that or someone's trying to put doors on the field.
The question is: "Slippery slope, park or mountain?"
The competition, both for its merely organizational aspect and for what it means of reflection on the city is the topic of conversation among all the Barcelona architects.
It's almost a recurring theme when two members of this ancient chosen caste recognize each other in an elevator.
And this fact gives rise, precisely, to one of the few coincidences between the opinions of three architects from Barcelona, and university professors, who have presented themselves.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel Mòdol and Marta Bayona: the competition is timely.
For Roldán, after tackling the coastal front, it is "necessary" to debate "the mountain front", since the speech of Ildefons Cerdà, the one about the green apples, has not been carried out.
"It is to be assumed that the largest park in Barcelona is the beach.
Among other things, because of its great accessibility.
The architect, for whom the title 'Collserola's doors' is a 'lexical trap', says that it is not necessary to think of them 'as entrances to a park, but as the delimitation of areas where action is needed'.
Mòdol, like Roldán and Bayona with experience in the urban world, calls the proposal an "intellectual challenge" with "some dangers".
The Commission has also proposed that the Commission should submit a proposal to the Council for a directive on the protection of the environment by preventing and combating pollution from ships and aircraft.
The first fear is the very delineation of boundaries on where to build.
"To limit something is to fix the next step", that is, to overstep it.
"We need to think about new urban planning instruments, because the current ones [referring to the General Metropolitan Plan (PGM) ] can lead to real disasters".
More closely related to the question, Mòdol argues that, simplifying, the Collserola slope "can be understood as a park, the one in Barcelona, not", for a purely topographical question.
Mòdol recalls that there is already a work done by the Patronat of Collserola that "should not fall into a sack", although he is grateful for the opportunity that the town hall offers his guild to intervene in this project "from the first moment".
And even more, he understands that the proximity of the mountain to the city is the safe passage that allows architects to enter the debate, but "doubt" whether it is this technical profile that should lead the multidisciplinary teams ("everything a hit", he points out) that have had to be created: "Architects should be only a tool".
Bayona insinuates that the answer to the question that gives the title to this piece is complex, because the basis of the competition lacks a global vision of Collserola: "16 transversal competitions have been called - he says - in the mountain-sea sense, but there is no longitudinal reading, which sees and understands the area as a whole".
This leads, at least in his case, to the fact that he has chosen to participate in all 16 competitions.
Otherwise, a project for one of the doors may clash in program and definition with that of the architect of the next door.
In his opinion, the city council should ensure that the strip immediately above the Ronda de Dalt should provide, throughout its length, a zone of equipment that would make a smooth transition between the city and the green.
Casino forgives Jonas Larrazabal and he is free.
After 72 days of arraigation, the legal representative of the Casino Red granted the brother of the mayor of Monterrey the pardon of the process that was followed for alleged blackmail
After 72 days in prison, Manuel Jonás Larrazábal will be released after the legal representative of Casino Red granted him a pardon before the Second District Criminal Court, which is pursuing a process for blackmail against the brother of the mayor of Monterrey.
After the attack on Casino Royale, the owner of Casino Red, Sergio Gil García, made public a series of photographs and videos in which Manuel Jonás allegedly demanded the payment of an economic fee so that the regional council allowed the clandestine operation of the betting house.
After the public complaint, the state prosecutor's office opened a criminal case against the brother of the mayor of Panista and on September 2 was arrested and arraigado for 30 days.
After four hours before the Public Ministry Agent 3 in Patrimonial Offences, he was transferred to the Casa de Arraigo 1, located in the Old Quarter of the state capital.
He remained there for the next 49 days after a second arrest warrant was issued after the Public Ministry agent dismissed the crimes of cohecho and organized crime.
On October 19, he was transferred to the Cadereyta prison allegedly for blackmailing the owners of Casino Red with one and a half million pesos; however, he only stayed a few hours in the medium security prison since there were death threats against him.
The authorities allowed him to continue the trial in the municipal cells of San Nicolás de los Garza.
On October 25, an arrest warrant was issued by the secretary of the Second District Penal Court, Jorge Yánez, who said that after almost two months of investigations, sufficient evidence was found to determine the guilt of Jonás, such as the collection of 1.5 million pesos from the representatives of the betting house in exchange for allowing the operation of the same.
This Monday, the legal representative of Casino Red, Víctor Aldo García Gómez, went to judge José Luis Pecina to request forgiveness for the brother of the mayor; so that in the next few hours he could regain his freedom.
During the legal proceedings, the agent of the Public Ministry attached to the Court, Ramiro Arias, questioned García Gómez whether the damage had been repaired and which of the partners of the betting house was the one who granted the pardon, although the lawyer tried to reserve the name.
Based on the 197/2011 file, Jonás Larrazábal is granted a legal pardon and thereafter no claim can be made regarding the process that was followed; in addition, no reparation of damage or punishment will be required.
After the hearing with the legal representative of the betting house, at about 15:50 hours, Larrazabal Bretón was ordered to be released immediately.
The secretary of the Court, Jorge Yánez, went to the jail of the municipality of San Nicolás de los Garza to notify Jonás that he has been legally pardoned and his file will be archived.
He will also notify you of the judge's order for your immediate release.
Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome gives details of the plane crash in which the Secretary of the Government, Francisco Blake, and seven other people lost their lives
The Secretariat of Communications and Transportation (SCT) reported that the results of the accident where the secretary of the Government, Francisco Blake Mora, and seven other people lost their lives, indicate that the helicopter directly impacted the ground in complete structural integrity, without the pilot being able to attempt a forced landing.
During a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transport, mentioned that before taking off the aircraft, the pilot found that the weather conditions were suitable for flying.
"Elements that seem to indicate the unit had several contacts with the ground, the blades had contact with trees at 25 meters where the unit lost the fuselage".
He also reported that the unit was designed for 19 people, so it had the necessary requirements to transport the staff.
In addition, he said that in the investigations made in the impact zone no appearance of pieces on the ground is reported.
"A search reported no parts or components of the ship elsewhere, the impact was presented in a structural form.
"The helicopter was designed for 19 passengers, it had adequate requirements to transport the passengers.
The terrain has a seven-degree slope at 30 degrees of inclination.
For the time being, the secretary said that it is a priority to have the results as soon as possible; however, the investigation can last for several months, even could reach a year.
Gilberto López Meyer, director general of Aeroports and Auxiliary Services, said that at the time of the impact, the helicopter of the Presidential Staff was operating at cruising speed and that this happened on a soft ascending terrain.
"This information strengthens the hypothesis of a normal cruise operation at the time of impact", he said.
At the press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez Jácome, listed six relevant elements in the investigation:
Visual flight:
According to the aeronautical regulations the flight was performed under the visual flight rules, this implies that the crew must have visibility during the flight and the terrain.
The weather conditions:
Reports at the AICM located adequate conditions at takeoff, as the aircraft advanced towards the border area between the DF and the State of Mexico layers of clouds were present at low altitude.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to the cloudy conditions the crew has looked for a lower elevation and greater visibility towards the valley of Cuernavaca.
Location of impact.
The impact coordinates and the aircraft's last radar record match, so there was probably no loss of control or alteration in flight path before the impact.
Dispersion of aircraft debris in a restricted area:
The information available so far suggests that the impact occurred on a straight and sideways trajectory.
The pattern of dispersion of debris from the aircraft suggests that the helicopter struck the ground in structural integrity.
No evidence of fire or explosion detected:
At the crash site, no evidence of any kind of explosion or fire has been revealed in the wreckage.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that he may have had multiple contacts with the ground.
During field work, parts of the aircraft were found at an elevation of 9,200 feet above mean sea level, the terrain having a slope ranging from seven degrees to 30 degrees of inclination.
The photographs show the sequence in which it was predictably dismantled along that route.
The information provided appears to indicate that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts on the ground.
After a thorough search of a wider area than the designated site, around the crash, no scattered parts of the aircraft have been found, which strengthens the presumption that the impact occurred in conditions of structural integrity.
MSS announces protocol to find gene of obesity
Social Security is leading a research project to discover the gene of obesity in children and young people; it is supported by specialists from the IPN
The Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) announced that it is conducting research to discover the gene of obesity in children and young people, called the 'Genetics of childhood and adolescence obesity' protocol, which will allow for markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Hospital of Specialties of the National Medical Center Siglo XXI, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was integrated.
The team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The population is invited to participate in the research, whether or not they are entitled, to go to the participating sports units of the IMSS in the Valley of Mexico, where the tests are carried out to minors, every Saturday from 8:00 am.
He noted that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (Eastern State of Mexico) and that since October 8, the activity is held in the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Unit (Eastern State of Mexico).
Once the target of 500 or 600 children is met, the study will continue in the Independencia Sports Unit (south of the Federal District) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to know the components and the importance of genetics with respect to the development of obesity and to identify in children and young Mexicans risk factors to prevent the occurrence of chronic degenerative diseases.
The World Diabetes Day is being celebrated on November 14th, and the aim is to bring together 3,000 children and youth between the ages of 6 and 14, with the consent and supervision of their parents, to apply specific questionnaires about food.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases, in order to avoid risk factors for conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that on Saturdays all participants undergo anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure, glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin levels, and genetic tests (they seek to identify genes associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López said that this investigation is due to the concern of health professionals for the alarming increase in weight in children.
'The health surveys of 1999 and 2006 indicated that in just six years there was an increase, in the case of boys, of 77 percent in obesity, and of girls of 47 percent; in terms of overweight also a dramatic rise was observed,' the specialist of the IMSS stressed.
He said the rationale for the search for the markers is based on the fact that the country's population differs from others by its genetic history.
He reported that on average, the Mexican has 65 percent American Indian heritage, 30 percent European and five percent African and this condition is reflected in genes associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translate into the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and which is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants is the comprehensive evaluation of the children, which allows detecting whether they present any degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark-colored folds (acantosis) on his neck and forearm, which indicate the likelihood of metabolic disturbances and even prediabetes.
The information is kept confidential, and doctors give it in writing to parents, who are then told about each measurement and lifestyle change they need to make to prevent disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentarism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, sitting in front of the television most of the day and using means of transportation instead of walking short distances.
It is also due to the high caloric intake, i.e. the higher consumption of sugary drinks, of carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburger, etc.) with high fat and protein content and the genetics that are analyzed in this protocol.
Asphalt from UNAM would prevent potholes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry of UNAM, develops polymer-modified asphalt to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental conditions and temperature
If the signals sent by the pavimento were attended, it would not be necessary to repair about 200 thousand potholes each season of rains in the Metropolitan Zone of the Valley of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher of the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who assured that if the process of construction and maintenance of an asphalt pavimento is adequate, the potholes could be reduced in quantity or, even, eliminated completely.
In his lecture A technological opinion of the bumps, delivered in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory he was in charge of was developing asphaltes modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve its performance and, therefore, the formation of potholes.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of petroleum, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, some of high molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and others of low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behaviour of asphalt is that at high temperatures, close to 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees Celsius its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees Celsius it presents an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that the strength of the asphalt is not uniform on the streets, but is changing during the day according to environmental conditions and temperature, the chemical engineering specialist warned.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered by flexible pavement, which is composed of six layers of materials, of which the last three involve asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphalt carpet, made up of small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the pebbles that make up the folder, he noted, is bathed in asphalt.
By passing the vehicles and generating forces, it allows the forces to be diffused very well on the pavement.
If it were modified asphalt, they would spread even better, the chemical engineer opined.
Above the asphalt carpet, it abounded, a last layer called rolling carpet is placed, which is made of a material of fine stone, that is, a sand that also bathes in asphalt.
As this is the layer that will be in contact with the tires of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt carpet and provide friction on the road.
As the part of the pavement that will receive and spread the forces, the rolling carpet also requires to have the appropriate thickness and the material of which it is made must be taken care of.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he said, because it considerably affects the performance of the asphalt folder.
When the ground becomes wet, water diffuses into the interior of the carpet and is difficult to get out, this causes softening of all the layers of the pavement and, therefore, the formation of potholes.
In the process of forming a pothole, he said, the first to wear out is the bearing film and only afterwards is the asphalt carpet affected, but the damage does not happen instantly, but is a process that should be addressed at the first signals with appropriate maintenance programmes.
He also explained that vehicle load is another important factor in the formation of potholes and, therefore, the thickness of each of the pavement layers should always be in relation to vehicle load and ensure that it is met, to avoid frequent potholes.
