Japan rebounds after earthquake
GDP grows by 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and ends the downward spiral that began in March
Since last March, the Japanese economy has been paralysed, still recovering from the devastating earthquake that turned into a nuclear crisis, the worst catastrophe that the Japanese country has suffered since World War II.
The first estimates of the Tokyo government put the material losses at $300 billion, a blow that, despite the difficult world context, seems to have subsided.
After three consecutive quarters of declines, the Gross Domestic Product data between July and September served to turn the page, definitively: GDP increased by 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and 6% in annualized rate.
The second quarter - for the Japanese, the fiscal year starts in March 2012 - also saw the fastest growth rate since January to March 2010.
The recovery is explained, in part, by the uptick in the purchase of machinery to restore areas devastated by the earthquake and subsequent tsunami.
In fact, firms increased their investments by 1.1%, compared to the 0.9% decline in capital expenditure observed from January to March, the first reversal after six months of uninterrupted increases.
However, the real upturn in the Japanese economy is not based solely on the Keynesian impulse to take advantage of crises to strengthen - or rebuild - infrastructures, to use shortcomings to grow from scratch.
Japan has awakened, above all, thanks to the evolution of domestic consumption, which now represents 60% of Japanese GDP.
This variable climbed 1%, driven by increased spending on vehicles, travel and leisure activities.
