However, according to the experts, who have also studied the situation in all countries where such practices have been legalized or do not constitute a criminal offence, there is no evidence that the fact that they are not considered a criminal offence has not led to an abuse of their application, i.e. the use of euthanasia or assisted suicide with incompetent persons or those who have not given their consent.
The report also calls for the adoption of a new law on the protection of the environment, which will be applied to all the countries of the European Union.
"In Canada, euthanasia is practiced, although it is clearly illegal".
"Assisted suicide is a common practice in Canada, although it is clearly illegal", explains Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians in favour of euthanasia
Recall that 85% of Canadians have already spoken out in favor of euthanasia, since they believe that it would allow people whose death is imminent to alleviate their suffering, according to a survey by Angus Reid conducted in 2010.
Furthermore, 66 percent believe that legalizing euthanasia will not mean that the lives of the elderly or the disabled are less valuable.
As for those who have committed assisted suicide, 41% of the respondents think that no legal proceedings should be initiated against them.
The situation is not so clear as regards the maintenance or interruption of the health care of a patient, according to the authors of the report.
In addition, among its recommendations, it suggests that the withdrawal of health care, if legally refused, should not be a criminal offence.
The Committee of Experts also calls for health professionals to be trained in the duty to respect the fact that a patient refuses care at the end of his life without fear of facing a complaint.
On palliative care, the committee calls for governments, health care institutions and doctors to work together to ensure the best palliative care, and not just for cancer.
The Committee also calls for the introduction of a new system of health insurance for the elderly, which would be a new system for the elderly.
Other experts express reservations
Other experts in the field of health law have already expressed their reservations regarding the findings of the Royal Society of Canada experts' report.
Pierre Deschamps, a specialist in health law, has described the position of the experts who signed the report as "extreme", not least because the practice of euthanasia is not limited to terminally ill patients.
"This leaves the door open to a situation where someone who is tired of living and is over 18 years old can ask for help to commit suicide", says Deschamps, who consulted a summary of the report yesterday.
Mr Deschamps also points out that the authors of the report seem to give priority to personal autonomy over any other value in society.
But, he adds, "in society, there are labels and limitations".
Health law expert Margaret Somerville also expressed her "strong opposition" to the report's conclusions, which she called a "manifesto in favor of euthanasia".
Margaret Somerville, who is also a member of the Royal Society of Canada, particularly challenges the lack of abuse in certain countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are legal, such as the Netherlands and Oregon.
