The Social Democratic/Christian Democratic grand coalition government in power in Austria decided on Tuesday to include in the constitution a budgetary "gold rule" to reduce the public deficit and thus avoid a possible downgrade of Austria's sovereign rating by the credit rating agencies (triple A).
It was the Social Democrat Chancellor Werner Faymann himself who announced this decision after a Council of Ministers meeting, when the Austrian public debt reached 74.6%, a figure far above the 60% ceiling fixed by the Maastricht Treaty, but clearly below the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
