Energy policy:
Facts must be worth more than dogmas.
If there is one subject which cannot be dealt with by taking short-term considerations or simply by thinking about emotions, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly influence the purchasing power and competitiveness of firms.
It is appropriate that an election should be the time to reflect on such issues and on the place of nuclear energy.
The debate will only be useful if it looks at the overall economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, on rational data.
Now that we're seven billion people on the planet, the demographic evolution will mean that electricity demand will double by 2050, unless a huge part of the world's population is deprived of a vital element.
At the same time, we must address the growing shortage of fossil resources to continue producing electricity continuously, not to mention the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate change, a topic that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
Germany is therefore alone in its decision to abandon nuclear energy.
This is not the case in Belgium, which is obliged to find a source capable of replacing it, or in Switzerland, which is only interested in building state-of-the-art power stations.
On the other hand, the UK, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name a few, are moving forward with determination with their projects.
The United States, for its part, after Fukushima decided to add a unit to its park, resuming the construction of a power plant interrupted after the Three Mile Island accident.
The German model, based on renewable energy sources, is sometimes presented as an example, but the reality is the opposite.
The choice of Berlin will mean higher electricity prices, greater energy dependence on imported gas, particularly from Russia, and higher CO2 emissions from the construction of gas and coal power stations.
In a few months, the harmful effects will be noticeable.
The case of Denmark should be considered.
Europe's leader in the wind sector, from which it gets 30% of its electricity, it is also one of the largest users of coal and gas due to the intermittency of the wind; for this reason, its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are, respectively, 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbours pay an electricity bill 40% higher than that of French households.
In a globalised economy, the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of the maintenance of industrial productivity on the national territory, while French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
For that reason, any significant reduction in nuclear energy would mean a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would undermine the realism of the wonderful statements about the re-industrialization of our country and the defence of our purchasing power.
This is a price which the vast majority of French people refuse to pay and, in fact, do not express any opposition in principle to this type of energy, as the polls show.
Let us remember that our country's energy policy has failed to build an industrial sector with 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Broadly export-oriented, it encompasses a galaxy of SMEs specialised in international markets and able to create non-relocatable jobs.
If France decided to abandon nuclear energy, it would mean the sacrifice of a large part of these SMEs and the loss of €6 billion of French exports of nuclear equipment and services every year.
What electrician would order an EPR designed to last 60 years when the manufacturer is scheduled to collapse?
To solve the nuclear power equation, one must admit that there is no miraculous source of electricity production, just as there is no diabolical source.
The development by Areva of low-emission CO2, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementary nature of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is essential to maintain the highest level of safety.
In France we have a safety authority which exercises strict and transparent control both over existing plants and over the construction of Flamanville.
Our teams, of recognized professionalism, are also obsessed with safety.
In half a century, the nuclear sector has suffered three major accidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, was produced under normal operating conditions; it had no consequences for people or the environment.
The Chernobyl accident was caused by the design of the reactor and by unforgivable human error.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident was due to two natural disasters of unprecedented scale, which killed tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident, as it did from the two before it.
Thanks to these developments and to cooperation between the safety authorities and French and German operators and manufacturers, the EPR is designed to withstand such phenomena.
While all the electricity players who want to build a power station are studying it, the interruption of its construction in Flamanville would be a great gift for the competitors of Areva and EDF, since it would leave them free to take the lead in the inevitable development of the nuclear sector.
It is both necessary and legitimate to seek the best energy options for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotion, dogma and partisan maneuvering dominate a debate so important for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Immigration - a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy pursued by Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various points of view: the saturation of the police, judicial and administrative services subject to the policy of figures, the compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of "country of human rights" of France.
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has jumped to the headlines, with the Minister of the Interior (see Libération newspaper of May 23) proclaiming from the past that France "does not need foreign talents, workers or waiters".
However, it is rarely analysed from an economic point of view.
The point is, on this issue, there is a lot of consensus between the left and the right.
On the right, Jacques Chirac set the tone by declaring in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed people should not be a problem for a country with nearly two million immigrant workers", while on the left, Michel Rocard set the tone by explaining that France "cannot take care of all the misery in the world" in 1990.
The only difference is the degree of generosity.
In 2005, both the left and the right shared the fear of invasion of the national territory by a crowd of Polish plumbers.
On both sides, immigrants are considered a burden to the French economy and society.
The only difference is in the degree of generosity with which they act towards immigrants.
The Commission's proposal is to be submitted to the Council by the end of the year.
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be electorally profitable, but economically it's very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent work summarising the latest knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of migratory flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries that receive immigrants.
Limiting immigration weakens growth and harms employment.
Fears about the impact of immigrants are based on the idea that immigrants can replace national workers, particularly low-skilled workers, by pushing for lower wages.
But experience shows that in reality immigrants are more complementary than substitutes for national workers and are mainly employed in sectors where there is a lack of employment.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national workers and higher-skilled immigrants in dynamic sectors where training does not meet the demand for personnel.
A positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country lacking in anaesthetists, the complementarity between nationals and immigrants causes the arrival of the latter to have a positive influence on the salaries and employment of nationals.
In view of the above, Giovanni Peri calculated that a 1% increase in migration flows would mean a rise in real wages in the long term of between 0.6 and 0.9%.
And, not to mention the fact that the diversity that immigrants bring to the world contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (there is a large proportion of naturalized American Nobel laureates and companies like Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Immigrants are also net contributors to social systems, as they contribute on average 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The International Labour Organisation calculates, for example, that in Germany an immigrant who reaches the age of 30 will make a net contribution (income minus expenditure) of EUR 150 000 to public budgets on average over his whole lifetime.
At the beginning of his term, Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to go looking for the points of growth that were missing "with his teeth".
Those teeth, which deterred immigrants, had exactly the opposite effect.
Europe has invented democracy, it only needs to think of a European democracy
Democracy is a precious asset, but it is also fragile.
The European continent should be able to remember this because, although it was invented in Athens over two thousand years ago, throughout the 20th century it has suffered the tragedies of the World War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the Gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some may have thought that for democracy to win out over its enemies, it would be enough to exercise the vote in the most direct way possible.
We know, since Napoleon "the Little", that it was something thought out.
Universal suffrage, although a necessary condition for democracy, is not sufficient on its own and can even become an 'instrument of oppression', as the Republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, a separation and control of powers, an education, lights, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis we are experiencing in Europe is an economic crisis, but it is about to become a political and democratic crisis.
The palinody of the true-false Greek referendum had, in this respect, a double revealing effect: it showed the need for a powerful return of the political sphere, but also the worrying feeling of its impossibility, of its incongruity.
He must reflect on this ambivalence in order to overcome it.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic battle have now shifted and that in many cases the Republican soldiers are no longer advancing in the right direction.
We shall not win if we demand a succession of national referendums, organised according to need and in a disorderly way.
A blank signature to the absolute European monarch or a stop to the vacuum of the nationalist hole: what options for the citizen!
No, we do not want to make a coup d'état, but a common exercise, a full exercise, a quiet and continuous exercise, of options and democracy, this time on a European scale.
There is no crisis in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal (in fact, we would not know where to end the list), because there is only one crisis, the crisis of Europe.
The whole of Europe is being pushed around by the markets and rating agencies, and is suffering from their impotence and lack of solidarity.
It is Europe as a whole that is being humiliated in the international arena.
We are concerned about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe, but it is the whole of Europe that is slowly losing sovereignty and, with it, each of its nations.
The most urgent thing is that popular sovereignty should regain the helm of the European project.
Because only together can Europeans reduce the burden of debt, free themselves from the markets and prepare their future through investment.
The way out of the crisis will require decisions at European level which cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, unless it is to lead us to disaster.
After having fought for a long time against this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors, the whole world is now calling for European economic governance.
I'll see to it.
But to think of it without greater political and democratic integration, and without it being lived as such by the citizens, would be a new folly and would lead us to a new dead end.
We must embark on a new stage in the construction of Europe.
To build the Republic in France, it was necessary to "make" republicans.
Revolution motivated by self-interest would not be enough.
This lesson is still applicable.
We must build a more economically integrated Europe.
It can only be achieved by building a Europe which is more democratic politically, a true European sovereignty of the people.
To build Europe, we must make ourselves European.
