Nord Stream, the new gateway for Russian gas to Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which links Western Europe directly to Russia via the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has already been put into operation.
It must supply gas to meet the needs of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with great pomp.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four Heads of State or Government, attended the opening of the Nord Stream, the new gas pipeline linking Russia directly to Germany under the sea, on the shores of the Baltic Sea, accompanied by orchestra music and a delicate buffet.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have together turned the steering wheel of the valve that controls the entry of Russian gas into the Western European grid.
The new pipeline will bring an additional 27.5 million cubic metres of Russian gas to Western Europe each year via a first 1,224 km link linking the St Petersburg region with the state of Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania.
A second pipeline should be completed by the end of 2012 and will supply a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, enough to cover all French consumption.
In addition, there is already talk of the possibility of building a third pipe along the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge project looks like a victory.
Poland and the Baltic States had strongly opposed the project.
Nord Stream will make it possible to supply gas directly to Germany, avoiding the overland route through third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
Suddenly, these two countries lose some of their power: it will be harder for them to influence Russia by threatening to close its access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare Nord Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
I mean, if the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting the Russian project, has obtained greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of Europe's energy, as the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years Russia has succeeded in making her vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, large gas consumers and with increasingly limited reserves, come to fruition.
'This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that links us organically,' said François Fillon at the inauguration of the pipeline, demonstrating how the major contracts in the gas sector are as much political as economic.
All this explains the broad smiles on the faces of Gazprom's executives, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The underwater pipe is made of steel coated with cement to protect against ship anchors.
It rests on the sea floor, at an average depth of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to World War II.
"A hundred of them had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution", says Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to extend the measures for the protection of fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs 242 Eiffel Towers and is not interrupted along its entire length by valves or maintenance stations.
A control platform in Swedish waters was planned, but the project was abandoned after the Swedes were reluctant to allow a Russian state company to establish itself permanently at sea off their coast.
"In the event of a breakdown, we will cut off the gas in less than a minute", says Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas from the pipeline will therefore be released into the atmosphere.
But builders consider leakage unlikely, since they have planned for joints that are forecast to leak once every 100,000 years.
The pipeline is monitored by a submarine robot, towed by a vessel, which performs external inspections, and by a device that travels along the inside of the pipeline.
It is shaped like a cigar, and is inserted into the tube, which is about three feet [one meter] in diameter, and is moved by the gas.
On arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three metres per second, it provides precise data on possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline has been designed to run for 50 years without any repair.
The circulation of the gas is guaranteed simply by the pressure.
At the beginning it's 200 bars and at the exit 100 bars.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the shares.
It was joined by Germany's E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), the Dutch Gasunie and the French GDF Suez group (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It is based in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased the entire gas transport capacity to Gazprom for a renewable period of 25 years.
'Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of how much gas is actually transported,' says Jens Müller.
The construction of the gas pipeline was financed by 30% from shareholders and 70% from bank loans.
The total cost of the project should reach 7.4 billion euros for the two pipes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment has reached 240 million.
But the minority shareholders are confident that they will not exceed their investment, since Gazprom alone assumes the risk of the expenses.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic at Lubmin, on a sandy coast planted with pine trees.
A series of valves, 15 feet high, form the gas outlet.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, the temperature and the specific characteristics of the gas on arrival, before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal has been receiving one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At full capacity, it will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine, a branded notebook.
Created half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to give people back the taste for writing.
It has an air of adventure, of hours of writing by candlelight.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognized, with its black rectangular pulp, its rubber, its leaves of broken white color, as aged by time.
However, the Moleskine notebooks in their current form were born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at that time to launch a notebook of design, but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, was responsible for the launch of the new product.
The libretto is inspired by an ancient production technique, mole skin, which refers to a varnished cotton that was used, among other things, to cover the banquets.
This type of notebook was highly prized by writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has adapted to the current taste an old and forgotten object, an icon of the avant-garde artists until the 20th century", says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become responsible for the brand in Modo Modo.
And he succeeded.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26%, to a volume of 12,7 million units sold.
The confidential production of the first few years, when only 3,000 notebooks were designed, has been far behind.
Moleskine goes beyond the borders of Italy and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the profile of the buyer, since the notebook attracts businessmen as well as students and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultured.
The small Italian company, which started with 12 employees, now has about 100 and, since 2008, has two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
He distributes his notebooks in bookstores, from the Fnac to small shops in the city centre, and has been able to impose his identity.
"We have adapted to the times and the need to write, despite the boom in e-mails", explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature goes hand in hand with the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has launched the exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, she also released a notebook with leopard covers, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, diaries, pens, computer cases... The brand covers a wide range of supports.
A success that is enviable: in autumn 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, thus writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate for disabled workers still so high?
Around 19% of disabled people are looking for a job.
The 15th Disabled Employment Week begins today.
Despite a determined public policy, implemented since 2005, the unemployment rate among disabled people is double the average rate: 19%, compared to 9% for the population as a whole.
How discouraging?
"No", says Éric Blanchet, director general of Adapt, the association that organises the week for the employment of the disabled.
"The progress made over the last 15 years is considerable.
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
"However, there is still a great deal to be done".
It should be mentioned that the disabled unemployed still face numerous obstacles to access to employment.
They tend to be older: 37% are over 50 (an average of 17%).
They have a low level of qualifications: 80% have not completed upper secondary school and, of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Lastly, long-term unemployment is widespread among them: 53% for the disabled, compared with 38% on average.
In other words, there are many issues that make it particularly difficult to return to the world of work and that "are the core of the problem", says Christian Grapin, general director of Tremplin, an association set up in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
Those are the objective obstacles.
In addition, there are those who are not mentioned; the mentality of the people advances, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Entreprendre association for the Cité pointed out that the directors surveyed had "a low level of knowledge about disabilities", with an "excessive representation of people in wheelchairs, physically or intellectually disabled".
The result: private enterprises with more than 20 employees are far from the target of hiring 6% of disabled workers, which was set in a law of 1987.
According to the latest available figures, dating from 2008, they reach a ratio of 2,6%.
"We are now at around 3%", says Pierre Blanc, director general of Agefiph, the body responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
The proof: the number of establishments 'subject to this contribution', as well as the amounts disbursed, have decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59 000 to 46 000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, has generated a lot of pressure for companies", explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects a real awareness, particularly among the larger groups".
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of companies with 20 to 49 employees have disabled employees on their staff, compared with 82% of companies with 100 to 199 employees.
